"title": "7444: sin offering",
"media_type": "Text",
"index_reference": "7444",
"language": "eng",
"review_level": "None",
"content": "<p>Offerings to make atonement for both moral and ritual offences. The NT sees them as foreshadowing the death of Jesus Christ as an offering for human sin.</p>\n<h2>Occasions when a sin offering was required</h2>\n<p>Unintentional sins against God's laws:\n <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:2\">LEV 4:2</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb9:7\">HEB 9:7</a>; \n<a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev5:1-Lev5:4\">LEV 5:1–5:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:20\">LEV 4:20</a> <em>The consequence of the offering is atonement and forgiveness.</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev12:6-Lev12:8\">LEV 12:6–12:8</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke2:24\">LUK 2:24</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev14:13-Lev14:31\">LEV 14:13–14:31</a>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark1:44\">MRK 1:44</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev15:15\">LEV 15:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev15:30\">LEV 15:30</a></p>\n<h2>The form the sin offering took depended on who committed the sin</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:3\">LEV 4:3</a> <em>a priest who sins</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:14\">LEV 4:14</a> <em>the sin of the community as a whole</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:22-Lev4:23\">LEV 4:22–4:23</a> <em>a leader who sins unintentionally</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:27-Lev4:35\">LEV 4:27–4:35</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev5:5-Lev5:6\">LEV 5:5–5:6</a></p>\n<h2>The ceremony when presenting an animal as a sin offering</h2>\n<h3>The guilty identify themselves with the offering before killing it</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:4\">LEV 4:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:15\">LEV 4:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:24\">LEV 4:24</a></p>\n<h3>Confession</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev5:5\">LEV 5:5</a></p>\n<h3>Blood, representing the victim's lifeblood, is put on the altar</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:25\">LEV 4:25</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:30\">LEV 4:30</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:34\">LEV 4:34</a></p>\n<h3>The best parts, being burned on the altar, are offered to God</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:8-Lev4:10\">LEV 4:8–4:10</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:26\">LEV 4:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:35\">LEV 4:35</a></p>\n<h3>Male members of priestly families may eat what remains</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev6:26\">LEV 6:26</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev6:29\">LEV 6:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev10:16-Lev10:20\">LEV 10:16–10:20</a></p>\n<h3>Special procedures for the offerings of the poor</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev5:7-Lev5:13\">LEV 5:7–5:13</a></p>\n<h2>The special ceremony for priests and the community presenting a sin offering</h2>\n<h3>Blood is taken into the sanctuary and placed on the altar</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:5-Lev4:7\">LEV 4:5–4:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:16-Lev4:18\">LEV 4:16–4:18</a></p>\n<h3>The rest of the animal is incinerated, not eaten</h3>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:11-Lev4:12\">LEV 4:11–4:12</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev4:21\">LEV 4:21</a> <em>emphasising the identity between the victim and the sin of the community</em></p>\n<h2>Significant occasions when sin offerings were made</h2>\n<p><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev8:14-Lev8:17\">LEV 8:14–8:17</a> <em>at the ordination of Aaron and his sons</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev16:1-Lev16:34\">LEV 16:1–16:34</a> <em>on the Day of Atonement</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs12:16\">2KI 12:16</a> <em>during Josiah's reformation</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr29:21-2Chr29:24\">2CH 29:21–29:24</a> <em>at the beginning of Hezekiah's reign</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra6:17\">EZR 6:17</a> <em>at the dedication of the second temple</em>; ; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezra8:35\">EZR 8:35</a> <em>when the exiles returned</em>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek40:39\">EZK 40:39</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek42:13\">EZK 42:13</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek43:19\">EZK 43:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek43:21\">EZK 43:21</a></p>\n<h2>The NT perspective on the sin offering</h2>\n<h3>Jesus Christ was the supreme sin offering</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Rom8:3\">ROM 8:3</a></strong>; <strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Cor5:21\">2CO 5:21</a></strong> <em>NIV footnote.</em></p>\n<h3>Animal sacrifices had limited value</h3>\n<p><em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb9:7-Heb9:10\">HEB 9:7–9:10</a></p>\n<h3>The death of Jesus Christ brings full cleansing and forgiveness</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb9:11-Heb9:14\">HEB 9:11–9:14</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Pet1:18-1Pet1:19\">1PE 1:18–1:19</a></p>\n<h3>Unlike earthly priests, Jesus Christ needed no sin offering</h3>\n<p><strong><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb7:27\">HEB 7:27</a></strong> <em>See also</em> <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Heb5:1-Heb5:3\">HEB 5:1–5:3</a></p>",
